A repeat Index of Biotic Integrity "IBI" survey was conducted from June 29-30, 2016 on Diamond Lake. One measure of a lake's health is the community of fish, plants and aquatic life it sustains. Certain species can't survive without clean water and a healthy habitat while other species are tolerant of degraded conditions. Examples of fish that require clean water are Tullibee, Rock Bass, and Bluegill. Species that are tolerant to degraded habitat are Black Bullhead, Common Carp, and Green Sunfish. The more intolerant fish to degraded habitat you have in the sample, the higher the score will be. An index of biological integrity (IBI) is a score that compares the types and numbers of fish or plants observed in a lake to what is expected for a healthy lake.

Diamond is a moderately large (1,607 acres), productive, and moderately deep (27 feet maximum) lake with moderate submergent and emergent vegetation located in Kandiyohi County. Seine hauls were conducted at 11 IBI stations with a bag seine of 50 foot width and 1/8 inch bar mesh in depths of 3.5 feet or less. A 15 foot wide and 1/8 inch bar mesh bag seine was used at 2 IBI stations. Dense aquatic vegetation or soft sediments prohibited seining at 5 other IBI stations. Near shore electrofishing was conducted at all 18 IBI Stations with a back-pack unit in water depths generally less than 2 feet deep. The 18 IBI Stations were spaced equally apart around the entire shoreline of the lake in a variety of near shore habitats. Each station was approximately 100 feet long. Two back-pack electrofishing runs were conducted at 13 stations with the initial run of 100 feet near the shore-water interface in depths of < 1 foot and the second run of 100 feet long about 10-20 feet from shore in depths up to 2 feet. Five stations were back-pack electrofished each at a distance of 400 feet from a boat due to increased water depth, vegetation and a muck bottom.

There were 19 different fish species (16 species from back-pack electrofishing, 13 species from seining) were captured from electrofishing and seining combined in the repeat IBI survey. Approximately 20 different fish species (17 species from back-pack electrofishing, and 14 species from seining) were captured from electrofishing and seining combined in the initial IBI survey a week earlier.

Fish species captured during the repeat IBI survey included gamefish (i.e. Largemouth Bass), panfish (Bluegill, Black Crappie, Yellow Perch, Pumpkinseed, Green Sunfish, and Hybrid Sunfish), large non-gamefish (Bowfin, Brown Bullhead, Common Carp, Black Bullhead and Yellow Bullhead) and small non-gamefish (Tadpole Madtom, Iowa Darter, Johnny Darter, Banded Killifish, Brook Silverside, Bluntnose Minnow and Fathead Minnow). Young of year species captured included Yellow Perch and Largemouth Bass in the seine hauls. Adult fish species captured only in seine hauls included Tadpole Madtom, Brook Silverside and Banded Killifish. Fish species captured only from electrofishing included Iowa Darter, Black Bullhead, Bowfin, Brown Bullhead, Common Carp and Hybrid Sunfish. Northern Pike and Central Mudminnow were only captured in the initial IBI survey. Black bullhead were only captured in the repeat IBI survey. The various species captured in Diamond are indicative of species present in most Spicer Area lakes.

THE WAE GILLNET CATCH INDEX (33.33 PER GN) WAS THE SECOND HIGHEST EVER RECORDED FOR DIAMOND LAKE (APPROXIMATELY 5 TIMES HIGHER THAN THE LAKE CLASS 27 MEDIAN). WAE SHOWED AVERAGE GROWTH RATES, HAD ALL SIZE CLASSES REPRESENTED, AND APPEAR TO HAVE A STRONG 1989 YEAR CLASS WHICH COULD PROVIDE GOOD ANGLING IN 1992. DIAMOND LAKE REGULARLY PRODUCES YEP CATCH INDICES THAT ARE HIGHER THAN MOST OTHER CLASS 27 LAKES (57.00 PER GN IN 1991). THIS PROVIDES A LARGE FORAGE BASE FOR PREDATORS (GROWTH RATES FOR ALL PISCIVORES WERE EITHER AVERAGE OR ABOVE AVERAGE). YEP GROWTH RATES WERE AVERAGE FOR AGES 1-3 AND ABOVE AVERAGE FOR AGE 4 (KEEPABLE SIZE YEP ARE HARVESTED). THE NOP CATCH INDEX (2.67 PER GN) WAS LOWER THAN THE MAJORITY OF CLASS 27 LAKES, HOWEVER, THE CATCH INDEX (PARTICULARY LBS PER GN) APPEARS TO HAVE IMPROVED SLIGHTLY COMPARED TO THE 1987 SURVEY. THERE WAS NO EVIDENCE OF A STRONG 1989, 1990 YEAR CLASS BEING RECRUITED TO THE FISHERY. THE BLC CATCH INDEX (6.00 PER GN) APPEARS TO HAVE IMPROVED COMPARED TO THE PREVIOUS 3 SURVEYS AND WAS HIGHER IN 1991 THAN THE MAJORITY OF OTHER CLASS 27 LAKES. REPORTEDLY, THE FISHING SUCCESS HAS ALSO IMPROVED WITH CRAPPIE IN THE 2-3 LB. CLASS BEING TAKEN (THESE SIZES WERE NOT SEEN IN THE SURVEY). GROWTH RATES WERE ABOVE AVERAGE AFTER AGE 1. THE BLG AND LMB STATISTICS SHOWED AVERAGE CATCH INDICES WITH AVERAGE TO ABOVE AVERAGE GROWTH RATES. BLB AND YEB HAVE MEDIAN TO ABOVE MEDIAN CATCH INDICES FOR CLASS 27 LAKES AND A SIZE DISTRIBUTION SKEWED TO LARGE-SIZE INDIVIDUALS (12.0 INCHES AND GREATER). CAP TRAPNET CATCH INDICES (NUMBER AND PARTICULARLY LBS PER SET) WERE THE HIGHEST RECORDED FOR DIAMOND LAKE.

Diamond is a moderate sized lake (1,565 acres) with a maximum depth of 27 feet. Waterclarity is fair. Nutrient levels are moderate compared to other local lakes. Agriculturalrunoff contributes most of the nutrient inputs via four inlets and several dairy/cattle farmslocated along the northwest, west, south shores. Other sources of nutrient inputs includeresidential lawn runoff and perhaps a few inadequate\outdated septic systems. The outlet(northeast side) connects to the Middle Fork of the Crow River. Submergent vegetation speciesand densities are greatest along the north bay, east shore, and "Dogfish Bay in the southeastportion of the lake. Curled pondweed (exotic species) often becomes overabundant and anuisance in the north portion of the lake. Blue-green algae blooms have been occurring morefrequently and with greater severity within recent years. Filamentous algae can also be aproblem especially within the "Dogfish Bay" Area and areas adjacent to the livestock farms.Emergent vegetation (hardstem bulrush, common cattail) occurs mainly along the north shorepoint, east shoreline, and "Dogfish Bay". The shoalwater substrates are composed of sand andgravel throughout most of the lake. The southeast portion of the lake "Dogfish Bay" is mostlysilt, muck, and marl. The surrounding watershed area is composed mostly of agricultural rowcrops with small areas of mixed hardwoods, residential development, and marsh areas. Theshoreline is primarily a mixed hardwood fringe on flat to gradual slopes with lake lotsaround the majority of the lake with the exception of "Dogfish Bay". Several marsh areasexist adjacent to the lake (northwest, west, south, east shorelines). Residentialdevelopment includes 355 homes/cabins, 1 resort (south shore), and Kandiyohi County Park #3(west shore). Diamond Lake is a popular walleye, northern pike, bluegill, black crappie, andlargemouth bass angling lake. It is also a popular recreational lake (swimming, boating,skiing, etc.). Past management activities have included the operation of a northern pikespawning area (Tait's Lake inlet) along the southwest shore, biennial walleye fingerlingstocking (about 1,200 lbs per stocking), monitoring of fish populations through lake surveysand specialized sampling, monitoring of harvest by anglers through a creel survey, monitoringof aquatic vegetation and water quality, and issuance of Commercial B permits for bullheadand carp removal. The Diamond Lake Association has taken an active role (i.e. enrolling inthe PCA Lake Assessment Program) in habitat and water quality protection. The 1994 averageweight was 6.0 lbs (trapnets). Diamond has an excellent reputation as a good fishing lake (walleye, northern pike,bluegill, black crappie). The moderate productivity of this lake is conducive for good growthof various species. However, increasing nutrient inputs will likely result in degradation ofspawning areas and other habitat. The loss of important fish habitat (bulrush stands) willresult in lower abundance of many gamefish species. Furthermore, increasing algae blooms andfilamentous algae growth as a result of increased nutrient levels will make Diamond lesspleasing to recreational activities. Reducing nutrient inputs requires the cooperation ofboth lakeshore owners and farmers/livestock producers within the watershed. Lakeshore ownerscan reduce nutrient runoff by using no/low phosphorous fertilizers on their lawns, plantingtrees and native grass buffer strips along their shoreline, and not disposing of grass/leaflitter within the lake. Also, lakeshore owners can maintain or increase important fishhabitat by transplanting bulrush, protecting remaining bulrush stands, and reducing the areafor mechanical/chemical control of native submergent vegetation. Exotic submergent species(curled pondweed) may be controlled by harvesting prior to bud formation in the spring,however this is still an experimental technique with limited knowledge about potentialsuccesses and failures. Area farmers need to practice more economical and conservationalfarming practices such as mulch till, minimum till, ridge till, or no till. For example,farmers leaving at least 30% crop residue on the fields after harvest can significantlyreduce both nutrient runoff and soil erosion. The long term benefits to farmers practicingconservational tillage techniques include lower operational costs (fuel, fertilizer inputs),reduced soil erosion, increased net profits, maintaining more current or similar yields, andsafer drinking water. Other important land management practices include planting adequatefenced natural grass buffer strips along feedlots and inlets within the immediate watershed.Also, landowners, the lake association, and the DNR need to work together on reducingexcessive feedlot runoff from several known sources. Fisheries management priorities shouldinclude continuing the operation of the northern pike spawning area, transplanting andprotecting of hardstem bulrush, protecting the fisheries/wildlife habitat within "DogfishBay", educating and informing landowners within the watershed about best land managementpractices, stocking walleye fingerlings more efficiently and effectively on a as needed basis(after two successive years of poor natural reproduction) rather than a systematic approach(every other year), monitoring the fish populations and directed angling pressure todetermine if harvest restrictions are necessary.

A targeted fall night electrofishing survey was conducted for young of year "YOY" (fingerling sized) Walleye on Diamond Lake during September 20, 2017. Diamond is a moderately large (1,607 acres), productive, and moderately deep (27 feet maximum) lake with moderate submergent vegetation located in Kandiyohi County. Abundant numbers of small Black Crappie, Yellow Perch and Shiner species were observed during 2014-2017 fall electrofishing surveys. Abundant Northern Pike numbers (9.3 fish/gillnet) were noted in the 2013 summer survey and recent ice out nettings. Walleye eggs were collected for the first time in 2014 on Diamond. Approximately, 60-70 quarts of Walleye eggs were collected for statewide and local quotas during 2014 and 2015. Approximately 191 quarts were collected during the early spring of 2016. We collected 90 quarts in 2017. Hatching success was good in 2014, but poor (<40%) during 2015-2017 due in part to early ice out and spring hatching. Walleye fry (800,000 fish per year) were marked with oxytetracycline "OTC" from the Spicer strain (Diamond, Koronis, and Rice) and stocked into Diamond during the springs of 2014 and 2015 as part of a 10% return for egg take. Diamond was stocked with 1.3 million OTC marked fry in 2016. Both OTC marked (475,396 fish) and unmarked (606,540 fish) fry were stocked in 2017.

The YOY Walleye catch rates were low in 2017 (4.00 YOY/hour, 6.24 inches average), 2016 (2.40 YOY/hour, 6.89 inches), 2015 (13.33 YOY/hour, 7.13 inches average), 2014 (8.00 YOY/hour), 2013 (6.00 YOY/hour) and 2012 (6.00 YOY/hour) fall electrofishing surveys. The 2011 YOY Walleye catch rate was high (104.52 YOY/hour, 6.94 inches). No fall electrofishing survey was conducted in the fall of 2009, but abundant yearling Walleye numbers (102.58 fish/hour, 6.21 inches) were sampled in a 2010 spring electrofishing survey. The Diamond Lake historical average YOY Walleye catch rate is 98.16 YOY/hour. OTC marked Walleye accounted for 100% and 14% respectively of the 2014 and 2015 fall electrofishing YOY Walleye catches. OTC analysis was not done on the few YOY Walleye captured in 2016 or 2017.

Prior to 2012, consistent and excellent Walleye natural reproduction had occurred in Diamond based on fall electrofishing surveys, OTC markings and historical data review. In recent years Walleye recruitment from natural reproduction or fry stocking has been poor due to poor early spring survival conditions and an abundance of predators in Diamond. Walleye natural reproduction and fry stocking success were generally poor in most area lakes during 2015-2017. A record early ice out date occurred on March 8, 2017 for Diamond. Typical walleye spawning occurs during mid-late April with hatching around mid-May. Generally, early ice out years are not conducive for good walleye fry survival in rearing ponds or lakes due to normal late April extended cold/cloudy weather periods that may negatively reduce plant plankton production and in turn reduce walleye food prey like zooplankton and aquatic insects.

Walleye fingerling or yearling stockings have occurred in response to consecutive low YOY Walleye numbers. The recent stockings occurred in 2004 (19,354 fingerlings, 925 pounds; 276 yearlings, 46 pounds; 487 adults, 348 pounds), 2013 (33,889 fingerlings, 1,405 pounds), 2014 (3,454 yearlings, 359 pounds; 1,314 fingerlings, 146 pounds), 2015 (47,091 fingerlings, 1,917 pounds) and 2017 spring (20,784 yearlings, 1,261 pounds; 207 adults, 84 pounds). The Walleye fingerlings/yearlings stocked into Diamond during 2015 and 2017 were from the local Spicer strain (Diamond, Koronis, and Rice) whereas previous fingerling or yearling stockings were from the Pike River Strain. Abundant yearling Walleye numbers were caught in the 2014 (54.00 fish/hour, 8.66 inches average) and 2017 (24.00 fish/hour, 9.24 inches average) fall electrofishing surveys, but these fish were likely from previous fall or spring fingerling/yearling stockings.

Current fish management activities on Diamond include monitoring the fish population on a periodic basis, protecting native aquatic vegetation through the permit process, participating in local watershed initiatives, preventing and educating about the spread of invasive species, conducting Walleye egg take operations when needed, and stocking various fish species as warranted. A fall night electrofishing survey is scheduled to assess Walleye natural reproduction in 2018. A resurvey of the Diamond Lake fish population is currently scheduled for 2018.

Diamond (1,565 acres) is moderately productive with a maximum depth of 27 feet. It isa popular fishing (walleye, northern pike, bluegill, largemouth bass) and recreational(skiing, boating, swimming) lake located about 4 miles northeast of Atwater, MN in KandiyohiCounty. A public boat access and campground is located along the west shore in KandiyohiCounty Park #3. Walleye numbers in Diamond (8.0 fish/gillnet) are currently low compared tothe historical average (19.6 fish/gillnet). Fall electrofishing surveys have been conductedsince 1993 to determine walleye fingerling abundance due to natural reproduction. Walleyenatural reproduction in Diamond was excellent to good from 1993-1997. However, walleyefingerling survival to adult size has been poor, thus resulting in poor fishing success for14-18 inch walleye during recent years. Walleye growth rates were good due to the abundantyellow perch forage base (31.0 fish/gillnet) present in Diamond. Poor walleye survival offingerlings to adult size is probably due to predation by various fish species (i.e.,northern pike, bowfin "dogfish", largemouth bass) and perhaps fish eating birds such as thedouble-crested cormorant. A potential option to increase adult walleye numbers in Diamondwould be to stock walleye yearlings instead of fingerlings in order to reduce predation byfish eating birds and predator fish species. The double-crested cormorant is a federallyprotected bird under the jurisdiction of the United States Fish & Wildlife Service,Department of Interior. Large numbers of double-crested cormorants have been observed feedingon Diamond by local residents in recent summers. Recently, the federal government has relaxedregulations concerning the killing of double-crested cormorants, however these only apply toprivate and state fish hatchery facilities. Private aquaculturalists and state hatcheryoperators may kill double-crested cormorants doing damage on their respective fish rearingponds. Local reports of angling success for walleye have been limited to catches of largewalleye (> 19 inches) usually during the fall, early ice conditions, or the first month ofthe summer opener. Northern pike were moderate in numbers (5.8 fish/gillnet) during 1997 for Diamond withan average size of 3 lbs. A 1997 spring electrofishing survey indicated good numbers (18.3fish/hour) and sizes (average size= 2.2 lbs.) of largemouth bass present in Diamond. Onelargemouth bass captured and released was 20 inches and weighed 5.3 lbs. Bluegill numberswere below average in 1997. However, local anglers have reported success at catching largebluegill (> 8 inches) in the past. The Diamond Lake Association is actively involved forimproving water quality of Diamond Lake. The MNDNR Spicer Fisheries Office manages Diamondfor walleye and northern pike as the primary species with bluegill, black crappie, andlargemouth bass as secondary species. Management priorities for Diamond Lake includeprotecting important fisheries habitat (hardstem bulrush stands), working with the localresidents to improve the lake water quality, encouraging local landowners to implement bestmanagement practices within the watershed (i.e., planting buffer strips, conservationtillage, using low/no phosphorus fertilizers, updating non conforming septic systems, propermanure/feedlot management, wetland restoration), maintaining adequate gamefish populationsthrough stocking as justified.

A population assessment was conducted on Diamond Lake during Mid-July of 2013. Diamond is a moderately large (1,565 acres), productive, and moderately deep (27 feet maximum) lake located in Kandiyohi County. There are numerous small inlets and one large inlet that drain primarily agricultural row crops via tile systems and wetlands into Diamond. A new perforated multi-culvert barrier was installed in 2012 at the largest inlet in order to prevent adult carp from Diamond entering into three shallow upstream lakes (Hubbard, Wheeler, and Schultz) to spawn and degrade water quality. Submergent vegetation species are varied and densities moderate in Diamond. Curly-leaf pondweed has been a nuisance especially along the north portions of the lake in the past, but has been less bothersome in recent years. Emergent vegetation present includes mostly hardstem bulrush (north point, east shoreline area) and cattail species (southeast bay). Shoalwater substrates of the main basin are mostly sand, rubble, and gravel. Silt and muck compose the majority of substrates in a shallow southeast bay. Mid-summer dissolved oxygen levels (>7.0 ppm) were good down to 21 feet deep during 2013. Water clarity was fair on July 22, 2013 (5.0 feet). Walleye natural reproduction is usually frequent and significant in Diamond compared to other Spicer Area lakes. Diamond is a popular lake for a variety of fish species which include walleye, northern pike, black crappie, bluegill, yellow perch and largemouth bass.

Black crappie numbers were abundant in 2013 (19.67 fish/gillnet) compared to the Diamond Lake historical average (6.01 fish/gillnet). The black crappie average size was moderate (0.47 pounds, 8.65 inches) in the 2013 gillnets. The 2013 catch rate of larger (>10 inches) black crappie was high (10.67 fish/gillnet). Black crappie growth rates were near or above the Spicer Area normal ranges for ages 2-7. The 2012 and 2009 year classes comprised 78% and 15% respectively of the 2013 black crappie gillnet and trapnet catch. Anglers had good success catching moderate to large size black crappie (2009 year class) in the 2013-14 winter.

Bluegill numbers were abundant in 2013 (36.83 fish/trapnet) compared to the historical average (12.99 fish/trapnet). The 2013 bluegill average size was small (0.09 pounds and 4.88 inches) from trapnets. However, we did observe local anglers catching moderate numbers of large sized (>0.5 pound) bluegill during the 2013 summer survey in Diamond.

A spring electrofishing survey, which best samples adult largemouth bass, was not conducted due to time constraints in 2013. We did sample low numbers of largemouth bass in the trapnets (0.25 fish/trapnet, 1.23 pounds average weight) during 2013 summer survey.

Northern pike numbers were abundant in 2013 (9.33 fish/gillnet) compared to the Diamond Lake historical average (4.68 fish/gillnet). The 2013 northern pike average size was small (2.63 pounds and 21.68 inches). The northern pike historical average weight is 2.73 pounds from gillnets. The 2013 catch rate of larger (>28 inches) northern pike was low (0.33 fish/gillnet). Northern pike growth rates were within the Spicer Area normal ranges for ages 1-3 and above the normal ranges for ages 4-7. The 2010 year class comprised 69% of the 2013 gillnet and trapnet catch.

Yellow perch numbers were abundant in 2013 (89.33 fish/gillnet) compared to the Diamond Lake historical average (45.44 fish/gillnet). The 2013 yellow perch average size was moderate (0.16 pounds and 7.10 inches) from gillnets. The 2013 catch rate of moderate sized (>8 inches) yellow perch was high (12.38 fish/gillnet).

Walleye were abundant in 2013 (15.00 fish/gillnet) compared to the normal range for similar lakes, but comparable to the historical average (16.73 fish/gillnet) for Diamond. Walleye sampled in gillnets during the 2013 survey were large (2.67 pounds and 18.22 inches). The walleye historical average weight is 1.82 pounds from gillnets. The 2013 catch rate of larger walleye (>20 inches) was high (6.00 fish/gillnet). Walleye growth rates were within the Spicer Area normal ranges for ages 1-8. The four prominent walleye year classes present in the 2013 gillnet and trapnet catch were from 2011 (27%), 2009 (25%), 2006 (20%) and 2005 (18%). Abundant numbers of young of year "YOY" walleye due to natural reproduction (>100 YOY/hour) were noted in fall electrofishing surveys of 2005-2006 and 2011 and yearlings in spring electrofishing survey of 2010. The YOY walleye catch rates were low (6.00 YOY/hour) in both the 2012 and 2013 fall electrofishing surveys. Recent walleye stockings included 2004 (19,354 fingerlings, 925 pounds; 276 yearlings, 46 pounds; 487 adults, 348 pounds) and 2013 (33,889 fingerlings, 1,405 pounds). Local anglers were reporting good catches of smaller walleye (12-14 inches) during the 2013 summer.

Black bullhead numbers were moderate in 2013 (15.00 fish/gillnet) compared the normal ranges of similar lakes, but below the Diamond Lake historical average (34.65 fish/gillnet). The 2013 black bullhead average size was large (1.10 pounds) from gillnets.

Current fish management activities on Diamond include monitoring the fish population on a periodic basis, protecting native aquatic vegetation through the permit process, participating in local watershed initiatives, preventing and educating about the spread of invasive species, and stocking various fish species as warranted. A fall electrofishing survey is scheduled to assess walleye natural reproduction in 2014. A resurvey of the Diamond Lake fish population is currently scheduled for 2018.

A fall night electrofishing survey was conducted for young of year "YOY" (fingerling sized) Walleye on Diamond Lake during September 29, 2015. Diamond is a moderately large (1,607 acres), productive, and moderately deep (27 feet maximum) lake with moderate submergent vegetation located in Kandiyohi County. Abundant numbers of small black crappie, yellow perch and shiner species were observed during both 2014 and 2015 fall electrofishing surveys. Walleye eggs were collected for the first time in 2014 on Diamond. Approximately, 60-70 quarts were collected for statewide and local quotas during 2014 and 2015. Walleye fry (800,000 fish per year) marked with oxytetracycline "OTC" from the Spicer strain (Diamond, Koronis, and Rice) were stocked into Diamond during the springs of 2014 and 2015 as part of a 10% return for egg take.

The YOY Walleye catch rates were low in 2015 (13.33 YOY/hour, 7.13 inches average), 2014 (8.00 YOY/hour), 2013 (6.00 YOY/hour) and 2012 (6.00 YOY/hour) fall electrofishing surveys. The Diamond Lake historical average YOY Walleye catch rate is 106.79 YOY/hour. OTC marked walleye accounted for 100% and 14% respectively of the 2014 and 2015 fall electrofishing YOY Walleye catches. Walleye natural reproduction and fry stocking success were generally poor in most area lakes during 2015. A rapid warmup (>50 F water temperature) during the spawning season probably caused poor fertilization of Walleye eggs. In addition a long term cold spell after the hatch probably reduced zooplankton production resulting in poor Walleye fry survival during 2015. The 2011 YOY Walleye catch rate was 104.52 YOY/hour (6.94 inches). No fall electrofishing survey was conducted in the fall of 2009, but abundant numbers of yearling Walleye (102.58 fish/hour, 6.21 inches) were sampled in a 2010 spring electrofishing survey. Recent Walleye fingerling or yearling stockings included 2004 (19,354 fingerlings, 925 pounds; 276 yearlings, 46 pounds; 487 adults, 348 pounds), 2013 (33,889 fingerlings, 1,405 pounds), 2014 (3,454 yearlings, 359 pounds; 1,314 fingerlings, 146 pounds) and 2015 (47,091 fingerlings, 1,917 pounds). The Walleye fingerlings stocked into Diamond during 2015 were from the local Spicer strain (Diamond, Koronis, and Rice) whereas previous fingerling or yearling stockings were from the Pike River Strain. A fall night electrofishing survey was conducted for young of year "YOY" (fingerling sized) Walleye on Diamond Lake during September 26, 2016. The survey was done with a boat set up with electrofishing equipment to evaluate fry stocking success in 2016. The electrofishing equipment puts electricity into the water and fish are attracted to the positive charge in the front of the boat. We then net the fish and take lengths and weights to determine what condition the fish are in (etc.). Diamond is a moderately large (1,607 acres), productive, and moderately deep (27 feet maximum) lake with moderate submergent vegetation located in Kandiyohi County. Abundant numbers of small Black Crappie, Yellow Perch and shiner species were observed during 2014-2016 fall electrofishing surveys. Abundant Northern Pike numbers (9.3 fish/gillnet) were noted in the 2013 summer survey and recent ice out nettings. Walleye eggs were collected for the first time in 2014 on Diamond. Hatching success was good in 2014, but poor in 2015 and 2016 due in part to early ice out and spring hatching. Walleye fry (800,000 fish per year) were marked with oxytetracycline "OTC" from the Spicer strain (Diamond, Koronis, and Rice) and stocked into Diamond during the springs of 2014 and 2015 as part of a 10% return for egg take. Diamond was stocked with 1.3 million OTC marked fry in 2016.

The YOY Walleye catch rates were low in 2016 (2.4 YOY/hour, 6.9 inches), 2015 (13.3 YOY/hour, 7.1 inches average), 2014 (8.0 YOY/hour), 2013 (6.0 YOY/hour) and 2012 (6.0 YOY/hour) fall electrofishing surveys. The 2011 YOY Walleye catch rate was high (104.5 YOY/hour, 6.9 inches). No fall electrofishing survey was conducted in the fall of 2009, but abundant yearling Walleye numbers (102.6 fish/hour, 6.2 inches) were sampled in a 2010 spring electrofishing survey. A resurvey was conducted on Diamond Lake during July of 2008. Diamond is a moderately large (1,565 acres), productive, and moderately deep (27 feet maximum) lake located in Kandiyohi County. There are numerous small inlets and one large inlet that drain primarily agricultural row crops via tile systems into Diamond. The outlet connects to the Middle Fork of the Crow River via a ditch system. The immediate watershed is primarily agriculture with residential, hardwoods, and wetlands composing the remainder. Diamond Lake is highly developed with 352 homes/cabins, one resort, and one county park/campground. The southeast bay "Dogfish" bay is the least developed portion of the lake. Submergent vegetation species are varied and densities moderate in Diamond. Curly-leaf pondweed has been a nuisance especially along the north portions of the lake in the past, but has been less bothersome in recent years. Pondweeds (narrow-leaf, sago, clasping leaf, etc.) were moderately abundant in 2008. The most common submergent species present during 2008 were muskgrass, narrow-leaf pondweed, water moss, northern milfoil, and clasping-leaf pondweed. Emergent vegetation present included mostly hardstem bulrush (north point, east shoreline area) and cattail species (Dogfish Bay). Shoalwater substrates of the main basin were mostly sand, rubble, and gravel. Silt and muck compose the majority of substrates in Dogfish Bay. Mid summer dissolved oxygen levels (>7.0 ppm) were good down to 25 feet deep during 2008. Total phosphorus levels were moderate (0.033 ppm) in June of 2008. Chlorophyll-a levels were low (2.30 ppb) in June of 2008. Water clarity was moderate to good during the 2008 summer (6.0 - 14.5 feet). Walleye natural reproduction is frequent and significant in Diamond compared to other Spicer Area lakes. Diamond is managed primarily for walleye, with northern pike, black crappie, bluegill, yellow perch, and largemouth bass managed as secondary species.

Black crappie numbers were abundant in 2008 (15.00 fish/gillnet) compared to the normal ranges for Diamond (25th=0.08, 50th=2.83, 75th=7.65 fish/gillnet) and similar lakes. The 2008 black crappie abundance in trapnets (10.67 fish/trapnet) was also above the normal ranges for Diamond (25th=1.29, 50th=3.08, 75th=5.88 fish/trapnet) and similar lakes. The black crappie historical catch rates are 4.99 fish/gillnet and 3.92 fish/trapnet. The black crappie average sizes were similar for both gillnets and trapnets (0.44 pounds and about 9.14 inches) in mid-July of 2008. The historical average weights were 0.23 and 0.38 pounds for gillnets and trapnets respectively. The 2008 catch rate of quality size (8.00 inches) and larger black crappie was high (14.25 fish/gillnet). Black crappie growth rates were above the Spicer Area normal ranges for ages 1-3. The 2005 year class comprised 96% of the 2008 black crappie gillnet and trapnet catch. There were low numbers of young of year "YOY" black crappie (2.67 fish/haul, 1.93 inches average length) captured in the 2008 shoreline seine hauls.

Local anglers had excellent success catching black crappie (8-10 inches average size) throughout the 2007-08 winter. Conservation Officers reported that limits of black crappie were common occurrence for anglers during this time period. There were 184 fish houses counted on Diamond during mid January of 2008 by DNR personnel. One local angler reported over 800 ice-fishing shelters on the ice during one weekend in late January of 2008 during the peak fishing success. In the 2008-09 winter, anglers reported moderate success for catching black crappie (10-12 inches average size).

Bluegill numbers were moderate in 2008 (5.25 fish/trapnet) compared to the normal range for Diamond (25th=2.99, 50th=4.50, 75th=6.87 fish/trapnet), but low compared to the normal range for similar lakes. The bluegill historical average catch rate is 10.61 fish/trapnet. The 2008 bluegill average size was large to moderate (0.28 pounds and 6.30 inches) from trapnets. The bluegill historical average weight is 0.23 pounds from trapnets. Local anglers reported catching low numbers, but large sized bluegill during the 2007-08 winter. The 2008 catch rate of quality size (6.00 inches) and larger bluegill was moderate (3.42 fish/trapnet). Bluegill growth rates were above the Spicer Area normal ranges for ages 1-4. The 2005 year class comprised 64% of the 2008 gillnet and trapnet catch. There were abundant numbers of YOY bluegill (114.17 fish/haul, 1.47 inches average length) captured in the 2008 shoreline seine hauls.

A spring electrofishing survey for largemouth bass was not conducted due to time constraints in 2008. Largemouth bass abundance was high in the 2003 spring electrofishing survey (27.00 fish/hour, 1.84 pounds average weight) compared to the Diamond historical average (17.24 fish/hour, 1.92 pounds average weight). There were moderate numbers of YOY largemouth bass (22.67 fish/haul, 2.20 inches average length) captured in the 2008 shoreline seine hauls.

Northern pike numbers were moderate in 2008 (3.75 fish/gillnet) compared to the normal ranges for Diamond (25th=1.67, 50th=3.75, 75th=4.92 fish/gillnet) and similar lakes. The northern pike historical average catch rate is 4.20 fish/gillnet. The 2008 northern pike average size was moderate to large (4.73 pounds and 26.80 inches) for Diamond. The northern pike historical average weight is 2.71 pounds from gillnets. The catch rate of preferred size (28.00 inches) and larger northern pike was moderate (1.50 fish/gillnet) in 2008. Northern pike growth rates were above or within the Spicer Area normal ranges for ages 1-7. The 2005 year class comprised 32% of the 2008 gillnet and trapnet catch.

Yellow perch numbers were moderate to abundant in 2008 (54.25 fish/gillnet) compared to the normal ranges for Diamond (25th=19.43, 50th=31.00, 75th=60.13 fish/gillnet) and similar lakes. A standard survey was conducted on Diamond Lake during 2023. Prior Diamond Lake standard surveys were conducted in mid-July. A targeted survey is generally used for sampling a specific kind of fish or time of year (i.e. spawning season, fall season, etc.) unlike a standard survey which samples a wider range of fish species during the summer months using standard methodology (i.e. standard time of year, set sampling stations, taking water clarity readings and oxygen/temperature profiles, etc.) and gears (i.e. lake survey gillnets, trapnets and possibly spring electrofishing for Largemouth Bass).

Diamond is a moderately large (1,565 acres), productive, and moderately deep (27 feet maximum) lake located in Kandiyohi County. Diamond Lake is highly developed with 352 homes/cabins, one resort, and one County Park/campground (2008 resurvey). The Diamond Lake County Park (55 camping sites) and main public access is located along the northwest side of the lake. A small public access is located on the east shore. Two Northern Pike Spawning Areas "NPSA" (NW corner and SW corner of the lake) had been operated adjacent to Diamond Lake in the past but are no longer used for rearing Northern Pike. Kandiyohi County Road #4 was rerouted around to the west side of the Diamond Lake County Park in 2018. The NPSA water control structure and fish barrier were removed due to the new culvert placement and road upgrades. There are numerous small inlets and one large inlet that drain primarily agricultural row crops via tile systems and wetlands into Diamond. A new perforated multi-culvert barrier was installed in 2012 at the largest inlet in order to prevent adult Common Carp from Diamond entering into three shallow upstream lakes (Hubbard, Wheeler, and Schultz) to spawn and degrade water quality. The outlet connects to the Middle Fork Crow River via a ditch system. The immediate watershed is primarily agriculture with residential homes, hardwoods, and wetlands comprising the remainder. The southeast bay "Dogfish" bay is the least developed portion of the lake. Submergent vegetation species (i.e., coontail, clasping-leaf pondweed, water celery, sago pondweed and northern milfoil) are varied and densities moderate in Diamond. Filamentous algae and water moss were also commonly occurring in Diamond. Curly-leaf pondweed has been a nuisance especially along the north portions of the lake in the past but has been less bothersome in recent years. Free floating vegetation species seen included star duckweed and lesser duckweed. Emergent vegetation present includes mostly hardstem bulrush (north point, east shoreline area) and cattail species (Dogfish Bay). Shoalwater substrates of the main basin are mostly sand, rubble, boulder, and gravel. Silt and muck compose most substrates in Dogfish Bay. Water levels were below average in recent years. Mid-summer dissolved oxygen levels (>7.0 ppm) were good down to 21 feet deep during 2023. Total phosphorus levels were moderate (0.033 ppm) in June of 2008. Water clarity was poor on July 27, 2023 (3.0 feet). Intense blue-green algae blooms were noted in Diamond during the 2023 summer. Diamond has been used as a Walleye egg take site for Spicer "Crow River" strain fish since 2014. Other local Spicer strain Walleye egg take lakes include Koronis, Rice and Elizabeth. Walleye natural reproduction was usually frequent and significant in Diamond prior to 2012 compared to other Spicer Area lakes. Zebra Mussels were documented in Diamond during 2018. Water clarity may increase in the future due to Zebra Mussel presence during the early summer months, but intense blue-green algae blooms will likely occur during mid/late summer months. Diamond is a popular lake for a variety of fish species which include Walleye, Northern Pike, Black Crappie, Bluegill, Yellow Perch and Largemouth Bass.

A nearshore fish survey was also conducted in the 2023 summer. Seine hauls were conducted at 16 Fish-based Index of Biologic Integrity "FIBI" stations. One seining station was sampled with a bag seine of 50 foot width and 1/8 inch bar mesh in depths of 3.5 feet or less. Fifteen seining stations were sampled with a bag sein of 15 foot width and 1/8 inch bar mesh at stations because of dense submergent vegetation. Near shore electrofishing was conducted at all 15 FIBI Stations with a back-pack unit in water depths generally less than 2 feet deep. The 16 FIBI Stations were spaced equally apart around the entire shoreline of the lake in a variety of near shore habitats. Each station was approximately 100 feet long. Two back-pack electrofishing runs were conducted with the initial run of 100 feet near the shore-water interface in depths of < 1 foot and the second run of 100 feet long about 10-20 feet from shore in depths up to 2 feet. Twenty fish species were captured in the near shore sampling gear. Low species numbers of intolerant habitat disturbance (Banded Killifish and Iowa Darter) were captured in Diamond Lake. Tolerant fish species captured included Black Bullhead, Common Carp, Fathead Minnow and Green Sunfish. The nearshore data were combined with trap net and gill net data from a standard survey to describe the fish community and provide a Fish-based IBI (FIBI) score. FIBI tool 2 was used for scoring and resulted in an FIBI score of 18 which is below the impairment threshold (45).

The FIBI uses fish community data to measure a lake's health, and the types of fish species present can help identify any stressors that may be negatively affecting the lake environment. In Minnesota lakes, certain fish species cannot survive without clean water and a healthy habitat (e.g. Blackchin Shiner, Iowa Darter, and Rock Bass), while other species are tolerant of degraded conditions (e.g. Green Sunfish). The FIBI score, composed of several fish community diversity and composition metrics, indicates the overall health of a lake by comparing it to what is expected for a healthy lake. For additional information on the FIBI, search for "lake index of biological integrity" on the mndnr.gov website. Data from this survey will contribute biological information about the health of the fish community to the North Fork Crow River Watershed assessment process in coordination with MN Pollution Control Agency.

Diamond is a moderately large (1,565 acres), productive, and moderately deep (27 feet maximum) lake located in Kandiyohi County. Diamond Lake is highly developed with 352 homes/cabins, one resort, and one County Park/campground (2008 resurvey). The Diamond Lake County Park (55 camping sites) and main public access is located along the northwest side of the lake. A small public access is located on the east shore. Two Northern Pike Spawning Areas "NPSA" (NW corner and SW corner of the lake) had been operated adjacent to Diamond Lake in the past but are no longer used for rearing Northern Pike. Kandiyohi County Road #4 was rerouted around to the west side of the Diamond Lake County Park in 2018. The NPSA water control structure and fish barrier were removed due to the new culvert placement and road upgrades. There are numerous small inlets and one large inlet that drain primarily agricultural row crops via tile systems and wetlands into Diamond. A new perforated multi-culvert barrier was installed in 2012 at the largest inlet in order to prevent adult Common Carp from Diamond entering into three shallow upstream lakes (Hubbard, Wheeler, and Schultz) to spawn and degrade water quality. The outlet connects to the Middle Fork Crow River via a ditch system. The immediate watershed is primarily agriculture with residential homes, hardwoods, and wetlands comprising the remainder. The southeast bay "Dogfish" bay is the least developed portion of the lake. Submergent vegetation species are varied and densities moderate in Diamond. Curly-leaf pondweed has been a nuisance especially in the north portions of the lake in the past, but has been less bothersome in recent years. Emergent vegetation present includes mostly hardstem bulrush (north point, east shoreline area) and cattail species (Dogfish Bay). Shoalwater substrates of the main basin are mostly sand, rubble, and gravel. Silt and muck compose the majority of substrates in Dogfish Bay. Water levels were above average in 2018. Mid-summer dissolved oxygen levels (>3.0 ppm) were good down to 18 feet deep during 2018. Water clarity was fair on July 17, 2018 (6.0 feet). Zebra Mussels were documented in Diamond during 2018. Water clarity may increase in the near future due to Zebra Mussel presence.

Diamond has been used as a Walleye egg take site for Spicer "Crow River" strain fish since 2014. Other local Spicer strain Walleye egg take lakes include Koronis, Rice and Elizabeth. Walleye natural reproduction was usually frequent and significant in Diamond prior to 2012 compared to other Spicer Area lakes. Diamond is a popular lake for a variety of fish species which include Walleye, Northern Pike, Black Crappie, Bluegill, Yellow Perch and Largemouth Bass.

Walleye abundance in the most recent 2018 standard summer survey (27.50 fish/gillnet) was above the normal ranges for Diamond and similar lakes. The 2018 Walleye average weight and length were 1.72 pounds and 15.60 inches from gillnets. The three prominent Walleye year classes present in the 2018 gillnet and trapnet catch were from 2016 (33%), 2015 (22%) and 2014 (15%).

Prior to 2012, consistent and excellent Walleye natural reproduction had occurred in Diamond based on fall electrofishing surveys, OTC markings. In recent years Walleye recruitment from natural reproduction or fry stocking has been poor due to poor early spring survival conditions and an abundance of predators in Diamond. Walleye natural reproduction and fry stocking success were generally poor in most area lakes during 2015-2017. A record early ice out date occurred on March 8, 2017 for Diamond. The most recent ice out dates occurred on April 7, 2020 and on March 29, 2021. Late ice out dates recently occurred on April 30, 2018 and April 20, 2019. Typical walleye spawning occurs during mid-late April with hatching around mid-May. Generally, early ice out years are not conducive for good walleye fry survival in rearing ponds or lakes if stocked in mid/late April. This is often due to extended cold/cloudy weather periods during April that may deter plant plankton production which in turn limits the emergence of early walleye food prey like zooplankton and aquatic insects.

A targeted fall night electrofishing survey was conducted for young of year "YOY" (fingerling sized) Walleye on Diamond Lake during September 23, 2019.

Diamond is a moderately large (1,607 acres), productive, and moderately deep (27 feet maximum) lake with moderate submergent vegetation located in Kandiyohi County. Abundant numbers of small Black Crappie, Yellow Perch and Shiner species were observed during 2014-2019 fall electrofishing surveys. Abundant Northern Pike numbers were noted in the 2013 and 2018 summer surveys (9.00+ fish/gillnet) and recent ice out trapnets. Walleye eggs were collected for the first time in 2014 on Diamond. Approximately, 60-70 quarts of Walleye eggs were collected for statewide and local quotas during 2014 and 2015. Approximately 191 quarts were collected during the early spring of 2016; 90 quarts in 2017; 25 quarts in 2018; and 113 quarts in 2019. It was common to catch numerous females between 6-10 pounds each, but males were few during spawn take.

Walleye fry (800,000 fish per year) were marked with oxytetracycline "OTC" from the Spicer strain (Diamond, Koronis, and Rice) and stocked into Diamond during the springs of 2014 and 2015 as part of a 10% return for egg take. Diamond was stocked with 1.3 million OTC marked fry in 2016. Both OTC marked (475,396 fish) and unmarked (606,540 fish) fry were stocked in 2017. Unmarked Spicer Strain Walleye fry were stocked on May 18, 2018 (930,788 fish) and May 14, 2019 (751,366 fish).

YOY Walleye numbers were abundant in 2019 fall electrofishing survey (110.00 YOY/hour, 7.03 inches). The YOY Walleye catch rates were low in 2018 (4.00 YOY/hour, 7.68 inches), 2017 (4.00 YOY/hour, 6.24 inches average), 2016 (2.40 YOY/hour, 6.89 inches), 2015 (13.33 YOY/hour, 7.13 inches average), 2014 (8.00 YOY/hour), 2013 (6.00 YOY/hour) and 2012 (6.00 YOY/hour) fall electrofishing surveys. The 2011 YOY Walleye catch rate was high (104.52 YOY/hour, 6.94 inches) due to natural reproduction. The Diamond Lake historical average YOY Walleye catch rate is 94.99 YOY/hour. OTC marked Walleye accounted for 100% and 14% respectively of the 2014 and 2015 fall electrofishing YOY Walleye catches. OTC analysis was not done on the few YOY Walleye captured in 2016 or 2017 fall surveys.

Prior to 2012, consistent and excellent Walleye natural reproduction had occurred in Diamond based on fall electrofishing surveys and OTC markings. In recent years Walleye recruitment from natural reproduction or fry stocking has been poor due to poor early spring survival conditions and an abundance of predators in Diamond. Walleye natural reproduction and fry stocking success were generally poor in most area lakes during 2015-2017. A record early ice out date occurred on March 8, 2017 for Diamond. Late ice out dates recently occurred on April 30, 2018 and April 20, 2019. Typical walleye spawning occurs during mid-late April with hatching around mid-May. Generally, early ice out years are not conducive for good walleye fry survival in rearing ponds or lakes if stocked in mid/late April. This is often due to extended cold/cloudy weather periods that may negatively reduce plant plankton production and in turn reduce walleye food prey like zooplankton and aquatic insects.

Walleye fingerling or yearling stockings have occurred in response to consecutive low YOY Walleye numbers. The recent stockings occurred in 2013 (33,889 fingerlings, 1,405 pounds), 2014 (3,454 yearlings, 359 pounds; 1,314 fingerlings, 146 pounds), 2015 (47,091 fingerlings, 1,917 pounds) and 2017 spring (20,784 yearlings, 1,261 pounds; 207 adults, 84 pounds). The Walleye fingerlings/yearlings stocked into Diamond during 2015 and 2017 were from the local Spicer strain (Diamond, Koronis, and Rice), whereas previous fingerling or yearling stockings were from the Pike River Strain. Abundant yearling Walleye numbers were caught in the 2014 (54.00 fish/hour, 8.66 inches average) and 2017 (24.00 fish/hour, 9.24 inches average) fall electrofishing surveys, but these fish were likely from previous fall or spring fingerling/yearling stockings.

Walleye abundance in the most recent 2018 summer survey (27.50 fish/gillnet) was above the normal ranges for Diamond and similar lakes. The 2018 Walleye average weight and length were 1.72 pounds and 15.60 inches from gillnets. The three prominent Walleye year classes present in the 2018 gillnet and trapnet catch were from 2016 (33%), 2015 (22%) and 2014 (15%).

A targeted fall night electrofishing survey was conducted for young of year "YOY" (fingerling sized) Walleye on Diamond Lake during November 3, 2022. A targeted survey is generally used for sampling a specific kind of fish or time of year (i.e., spawning season, fall season, etc.) unlike a standard survey which samples a wider range of fish species during the summer months using standard methodology (i.e., standard time of year, set sampling stations, taking water clarity readings and oxygen/temperature profiles, etc.) and gears (i.e. lake survey gillnets, trapnets and possibly spring electrofishing for Largemouth Bass). Fall electrofishing surveys prior to 2020 were conducted at three stations for a total of 30 minutes. A 2020 survey was conducted as part of a larger statewide research study to evaluate fall electrofishing catch effectiveness for different total shocking times. Six stations were sampled for a total of 120 minutes in both 2020 and 2021 surveys. Five stations were sampled for a total of 100 minutes in 2022. The water temperature was 50 F. during the 2022 fall electrofishing survey. Submergent vegetation was varied at different stations in 2022. Water clarity was moderate. We observed abundant to moderate numbers of adult Walleye, Northern Pike, Bluegill, Largemouth Bass, Black Crappie, shiner species and Yellow Perch in the 2022 fall electrofishing survey.
